revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox event | title = 2006 Hajj stampede | image = | caption = | date = {{Start date|2006|01|12|df=y}} | place = [[Mina, Saudi Arabia|Mina]], [[Mecca]], [[Saudi Arabia]] | coordinates = {{coord|21|24|48|N|39|53|36|E|display=inline}} | cause = | reported injuries = 1000+<ref name="markoliver">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/jan/12/saudiarabia.religion|title=Hundreds killed in hajj stampede|author=Mark Oliver|work=the Guardian|accessdate=29 September 2015}}</ref> | reported death(s) = 345+<ref name="markoliver"/> }} The '''2006 Hajj stampede''' resulted in the deaths of at least 364 pilgrims on 12 January 2006 during the [[Hajj]] in [[Mecca]].<ref name=bbc1>{{cite web|title=Hajj stampede: At least 310 killed in Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34346449|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref>
==Background== {{main|Hajj}} The Hajj is an annual pilgrimage in [[Mecca]] undertaken by able-bodied Muslims at least once in their lifetime. It consists of a series of rites including the [[Stoning of the Devil]] ({{lang-ar|{{large|رمي الجمرات|}}}} ''{{transl|ar|ramī aj-jamarāt}}'', {{abbr|lit.|literally}} "[[Rajm|stoning]] of the ''{{transl|ar|jamarāt}}'' [place of pebbles]<ref>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Richard Francis|authorlink=Richard Francis Burton|title=Personal Narrative of a Pilgrimage to El Medinah and Meccah|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXcOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA226|year=1857|page=226 |quote=The word ''jamrah'' is applied to the place of stoning, as well as to the stones.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=[[Abū Dāʼūd]] |title=Sunan Abu Dawud: Chapters 519–1337|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SwvYAAAAMAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Sh. M. Ashraf|quote=1204. ''Jamrah'' originally means a pebble. It is applied to the heap of stones or a pillar.}}</ref> which takes place in [[Mina, Saudi Arabia|Mina]], a district of [[Mecca]]. The stoning ritual is the last major ritual and is often regarded as the most dangerous part of the Hajj, with [[Incidents during the Hajj#Stampedes and failures of crowd control|stampedes]] occurring in the past.<ref>{{cite news|title=Satan stoned – most dangerous hajj rite|url=http://www.news24.com/World/News/Satan-stoned-most-dangerous-hajj-rite-20111106|accessdate=24 September 2015|agency=News24|date=6 November 2011}}</ref>
With a history of fatal stampedes at The Hajj – including a stampede which killed 244 in 2004<ref name="markoliver"/> – authorities in Mecca had taken steps in the hopes of reducing chances of another stampede, including the issuing of a fatwa extending the permitted hours of the ritual.
==Incident== [[File:Mina's tents.JPG|thumb|Mina camp sites, 2011.]] The stampede occurred when pilgrims fell over luggage that had been discarded in the rush to take part in the stoning.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/15/mecca-crane-collapse-saudi-arabia-king-sanctions-binladin-group | work = The Guardian| publisher = Guardian News and Media Limited | title = Mecca crane collapse: Saudi king sanctions Binladin group | agency=Agence France-Presse| date = 15 September 2015 | accessdate = 24 September 2015}}</ref>
